The Grand Historian, reading through the Spring and Autumn Annals, chronological tables, and secret records, could never help but lay down his book and sigh whenever he reached the reign of King Li of Zhou. He said: 'Alas, Master Zhi foresaw it!' (translated). When King Zhou fashioned ivory chopsticks, the Viscount of Ji sighed in dismay. When the Zhou way declined, poets based themselves on the bedchamber, and 'Guan Ju' was composed. (translated). When benevolence and righteousness decayed, 'Lu Ming' criticized it. (translated). When it came to King Li, his hatred of hearing his own faults made the ministers fear execution, leading to disaster. King Li fled to Zhi, and chaos began in the capital itself, leading to the Gonghe administration. After this, some ruled through force, the strong bullied the weak, and they raised armies without seeking the Son of Heaven's approval. Yet they upheld the royal house's righteousness, conducting punitive campaigns as alliance leaders. Power flowed from the Five Hegemons, feudal lords ran wild, extravagant and lawless, while traitorous ministers and usurping sons multiplied. Qi, Jin, Qin, and Chu were utterly insignificant during Zhou's prosperous era, their fiefs no more than a hundred li or fifty li. Jin blocked the three great rivers, Qi faced the eastern sea, Chu bordered the Jiang and Huai rivers, Qin relied on Yong province's natural defenses. The powers of the four seas rose in succession, each replacing the others as hegemonic lords. Those whom Wen and Wu praised and greatly enfeoffed all inspired awe and obedience. This is why Confucius clarified the kingly way, petitioning more than seventy rulers without success. He therefore observed the western Zhou court, discussed historical records and ancient traditions, rose up in Lu and compiled the Spring and Autumn Annalsâ€”from Duke Yin above to the capture of the unicorn during Duke Ai belowâ€”condensing the language and style, removing tedious repetitions, to establish principles of righteousness. The kingly way was complete, human affairs thoroughly covered. The disciples of the seventy worthies received his transmitted teachings orally, for there were passages of criticism, mockery, praise, concealment, and depreciation in the wording that could not be committed to writing. The Lu gentleman Zuoqiu Ming feared that disciples would each follow different doctrines, each comfortable with their own opinions, losing the truth, so based on Confucius's historical records he comprehensively discussed their sayings, completing the Zuo Tradition Spring and Autumn Annals. (translated). Duo Jiao wrote a commentary for King Wei of Chu, but since the king could not read the entire Spring and Autumn Annals, he selected examples of success and failure, finally producing forty chapters called the Duo Family Annals. During King Xiaocheng of Zhao's reign, his chancellor Yu Qing drew from the Spring and Autumn Annals above and observed recent trends below, also writing eight chapters called the Yu Family Spring and Autumn Annals. LÃ¼ Buwei was chancellor to King Zhuangxiang of Qin, and also looked up to revere antiquity, edited and collected from the Spring and Autumn Annals, gathered events from the time of the six states, making them into eight surveys, six discussions, and twelve records, calling it the LÃ¼ Family Spring and Autumn Annals. (translated). And like Xun Qing, Mencius, Gongsun Gu, and Han Fei and their followers, each collected fragments from the Spring and Autumn Annals' text to write books, differing greatly in their accounts. (translated). The Han chancellor Zhang Cang calendared the five virtues, the senior grand master Dong Zhongshu expounded the Spring and Autumn Annals' principles, and wrote quite extensively about them. (translated).

The Grand Historian says: The Confucians sever their meanings, the galloping explainers gallop with their words, they do not strive to comprehensively grasp beginning and end; (translated). Calendar keepers focus on years and months, several schools exalt divine destiny, while genealogical records and secret accounts merely note posthumous namesâ€”their language is brief, but grasping the essentials comprehensively proves difficult. Therefore I have created chronological tables for the twelve feudal lords, from the Gonghe administration until Confucius, making clear in tabular form the major outlines of rise and decline as criticized by scholars of the Spring and Autumn Annals and Discourses of the States, written in this chapter as an essential summary for those studying and interpreting ancient texts.
